In this distich sons seems certain, zgnz'st very probable. But quamquam is doubtful. Munro retained it, ‘though its acts are generally destructive.² This is awkward, especially in the ordering of the words; Maehly, Haupt, Sauppe, Baehrens, Sudhaus all reject it. Sauppe's quam qui, i.e. nec minus ille (mons) nobilis pio igni, quam qui (ignis) sons est, Baehrens' quam quo, sc. igni sons est mons, are neither of them con- vincing. On palaeographical grounds it seems more likely that quamquam represents quam—tam, and that the poet availed himself of a partially archaic formula like Tam magis— Quam magis (Aen. vii. 787) which Quintilian, ix. 3. 15, corn- pares with Catullus’ dum—dum = quoad—usque eo (lxii. 45), to give the effect of contrast to the pious same which Aetna on this single occasion won and its ordinary ill-same as a destroyer.
